        "title": "1. Pure functions â€” easy wins",
        "content": "\n**`articlesSaved`** â€” edge cases missing: empty slice, no matching lines, lines that start with `\"  -\"` but not `\"  - \"` (space-sensitivity), lines containing `\"  - \"` mid-string but not as prefix.\n\n```go\nfunc TestArticlesSaved(t *testing.T) {\n\tcases := []struct {\n\t\tname  string\n\t\tlines []string\n\t\twant  int\n\t}{\n\t\t{\"empty\", nil, 0},\n\t\t{\"no matches\", []string{\"starting...\", \"done\"}, 0},\n\t\t{\"single match\", []string{\"  - 'Title' (2026-01-01)\"}, 1},\n\t\t{\"multiple matches mixed with noise\", []string{\n\t\t\t\"connecting...\",\n\t\t\t\"  - 'A' (d1)\",\n\t\t\t\"progress: 2/10\",\n\t\t\t\"  - 'B' (d2)\",\n\t\t}, 2},\n\t\t{\"prefix without trailing space not counted\", []string{\"  -no-space\"}, 0},\n\t\t{\"substring not at start not counted\", []string{\"x  - 'nested'\"}, 0},\n\t}\n\tfor _, c := range cases {\n\t\tt.Run(c.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n\t\t\tif got := articlesSaved(c.lines); got != c.want {\n\t\t\t\tt.Errorf(\"got %d, want %d\", got, c.want)\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t})\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n**`truncate`** â€” edge cases missing: `n <= 0`, `n == 1` (branch explicitly short-circuits before ellipsis logic â€” verify it does *not* append `â€¦`), string shorter than `n`, exact length match, multi-byte/unicode input (function uses `len()`/byte slicing, will mis-truncate UTF-8 â€” worth a test that documents/catches this).\n\n```go\nfunc TestTruncate(t *testing.T) {\n\tcases := []struct {\n\t\tname string\n\t\ts    string\n\t\tn    int\n\t\twant string\n\t}{\n\t\t{\"shorter than limit\", \"abc\", 10, \"abc\"},\n\t\t{\"exact length\", \"abcde\", 5, \"abcde\"},\n\t\t{\"truncates with ellipsis\", \"abcdef\", 4, \"abcâ€¦\"},\n\t\t{\"n=1 no ellipsis room\", \"abcdef\", 1, \"a\"},\n\t\t{\"n=0\", \"abcdef\", 0, \"a\"}, // documents current `n<=1` behavior â€” verify intent\n\t\t{\"unicode input may mis-truncate\", \"madagasikara\", 5, \"madaâ€¦\"},\n\t}\n\tfor _, c := range cases {\n\t\tt.Run(c.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n\t\t\tif got := truncate(c.s, c.n); got != c.want {\n\t\t\t\tt.Errorf(\"truncate(%q,%d) = %q, want %q\", c.s, c.n, got, c.want)\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t})\n\t}\n}\n```\nNote: `n=0` case above will likely reveal a bug â€” `s[:n]` with `n=0` inside the `n<=1` branch returns `\"\"`, but comment above implies edge case worth locking down either way.\n\n**`(m) countSelected`, `(m) highlighted`, `(m) layout`** â€” straightforward, no subprocess involved.\n\n```go\nfunc TestCountSelected(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tif got := m.countSelected(); got != 0 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"empty model: got %d, want 0\", got)\n\t}\n\tm.selected[0] = true\n\tm.selected[1] = false // explicitly false entry should not count\n\tm.selected[2] = true\n\tif got := m.countSelected(); got != 2 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"got %d, want 2\", got)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHighlighted(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tif got := m.highlighted(); got != \"\" {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"before run: got %q, want empty\", got)\n\t}\n\tm.runOrder = []string{\"a\", \"b\"}\n\tm.runCursor = 1\n\tif got := m.highlighted(); got != \"b\" {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"got %q, want b\", got)\n\t}\n\tm.runCursor = 5 // out of range\n\tif got := m.highlighted(); got != \"\" {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"out-of-range cursor: got %q, want empty\", got)\n\t}\n\tm.runCursor = -1 // negative\n\tif got := m.highlighted(); got != \"\" {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"negative cursor: got %q, want empty\", got)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestLayout(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.width, m.height = 100, 40\n\tw, h := m.layout()\n\tif w != 100-sidenavWidth-4 || h != 40-6 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"got (%d,%d)\", w, h)\n\t}\n\n\t// guard clamps for tiny windows\n\tm.width, m.height = 5, 3\n\tw, h = m.layout()\n\tif w != 10 || h != 3 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"tiny window not clamped: got (%d,%d), want (10,3)\", w, h)\n\t}\n\n\t// zero-size (before first WindowSizeMsg)\n\tm.width, m.height = 0, 0\n\tw, h = m.layout()\n\tif w < 10 || h < 3 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"zero size not clamped: got (%d,%d)\", w, h)\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n",
        "level": 2
      },
      {
        "title": "2. State machine â€” `handleKey` / `Update`",
        "content": "\nUntested branches, by screen:\n\n**`screenPicking`**: up/down clamping at bounds (cursor already 0 / already len-1), space toggling on/off, `a` select-all, `enter` with 0 selected (defaults to all), `enter` with some selected, unrecognized key is a no-op, `q`/`ctrl+c` quits immediately (this screen is not `screenRunning` so quit should fire regardless of `pending`).\n\n**`screenLimit`**: `esc` returns to picking, `enter` with invalid input (non-numeric) is a no-op that stays on the same screen, `enter` with negative number is rejected, `enter` with `0` is accepted (explicitly documented as valid/unlimited), whitespace-padded input trimmed correctly. Note `enter` on valid input calls `startRun()`, which touches goroutines/subprocess â€” see Â§4 for how to isolate this.\n\n**`screenRunning`**: `q`/`ctrl+c` while `pending > 0` is a no-op (must not quit mid-run), `q` when `pending == 0` quits, up/down clamped at `runOrder` bounds, up/down triggers `refreshViewport`.\n\n**`Update` message handling**: `statusMsg` appends to the right provider's `lines` and sets `stateRunning`; only refreshes viewport if that provider is currently highlighted (verify it does *not* refresh for a non-highlighted provider â€” this is an easy regression to introduce silently); `doneMsg` with `err == nil` â†’ `stateDone`; `doneMsg` with `err != nil` â†’ `stateError` + appends `\"error: ...\"` line; `pending` decremented exactly once per `doneMsg`; `spinner.TickMsg` delegates without side effects on model state.\n\n```go\nfunc TestHandleKey_ScreenPicking(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\n\t// cursor clamps at 0\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyUp})\n\tif m.cursor != 0 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"cursor went negative: %d\", m.cursor)\n\t}\n\n\t// down moves, clamps at len-1\n\tm.cursor = len(providers) - 1\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyDown})\n\tif m.cursor != len(providers)-1 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"cursor exceeded bound: %d\", m.cursor)\n\t}\n\n\t// space toggles\n\tm.cursor = 0\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyRunes, Runes: []rune(\" \")})\n\tif !m.selected[0] {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"space did not select\")\n\t}\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyRunes, Runes: []rune(\" \")})\n\tif m.selected[0] {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"space did not deselect\")\n\t}\n\n\t// select-all\n\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyRunes, Runes: []rune(\"a\")})\n\tif m.countSelected() != len(providers) {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"select-all: got %d\", m.countSelected())\n\t}\n\n\t// enter with none selected defaults to all\n\tm2 := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm2.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyEnter})\n\tif m2.countSelected() != len(providers) || m2.screen != screenLimit {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"enter-with-none-selected did not default to all/advance screen\")\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHandleKey_ScreenLimit_InputValidation(t *testing.T) {\n\tcases := []struct {\n\t\tname        string\n\t\tinput       string\n\t\twantAdvance bool\n\t}{\n\t\t{\"valid positive\", \"10\", true},\n\t\t{\"valid zero (unlimited)\", \"0\", true},\n\t\t{\"negative rejected\", \"-1\", false},\n\t\t{\"non-numeric rejected\", \"abc\", false},\n\t\t{\"whitespace trimmed\", \"  5  \", true},\n\t\t{\"empty rejected\", \"\", false},\n\t}\n\tfor _, c := range cases {\n\t\tt.Run(c.name, func(t *testing.T) {\n\t\t\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\t\t\tm.screen = screenLimit\n\t\t\tm.limitInput.SetValue(c.input)\n\t\t\tm.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyEnter})\n\t\t\tadvanced := m.screen == screenRunning\n\t\t\tif advanced != c.wantAdvance {\n\t\t\t\tt.Fatalf(\"input %q: advanced=%v, want %v\", c.input, advanced, c.wantAdvance)\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t})\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHandleKey_ScreenRunning_QuitGuard(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.screen = screenRunning\n\tm.pending = 2 // simulate providers still running\n\n\t_, cmd := m.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyRunes, Runes: []rune(\"q\")})\n\tif cmd != nil {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"q must be a no-op while providers are still running\")\n\t}\n\n\tm.pending = 0\n\t_, cmd = m.handleKey(tea.KeyMsg{Type: tea.KeyRunes, Runes: []rune(\"q\")})\n\tif cmd == nil {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"q should quit once pending == 0\")\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestUpdate_StatusAndDoneMsg(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.runOrder = []string{\"midi-madagasikara\"}\n\tm.runCursor = 0\n\tm.statuses[\"midi-madagasikara\"] = &providerStatus{state: stateIdle}\n\tm.pending = 1\n\tw, h := 80, 24\n\tm.width, m.height = w, h\n\tm.vp.Width, m.vp.Height = m.layout()\n\n\tm.Update(statusMsg{provider: \"midi-madagasikara\", line: \"fetched 1\"})\n\tst := m.statuses[\"midi-madagasikara\"]\n\tif st.state != stateRunning || len(st.lines) != 1 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"statusMsg not applied: %+v\", st)\n\t}\n\n\tm.Update(doneMsg{provider: \"midi-madagasikara\", err: nil})\n\tif st.state != stateDone || m.pending != 0 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"doneMsg(nil err) not applied: state=%v pending=%d\", st.state, m.pending)\n\t}\n\n\t// error path\n\tm.statuses[\"midi-madagasikara\"] = &providerStatus{state: stateRunning}\n\tm.pending = 1\n\twantErr := errors.New(\"boom\")\n\tm.Update(doneMsg{provider: \"midi-madagasikara\", err: wantErr})\n\tst = m.statuses[\"midi-madagasikara\"]\n\tif st.state != stateError || !strings.Contains(st.lines[len(st.lines)-1], \"boom\") {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"doneMsg(err) not applied: %+v\", st)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestUpdate_StatusMsg_NonHighlightedProviderSkipsRefresh(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.runOrder = []string{\"a\", \"b\"}\n\tm.runCursor = 0 // \"a\" is highlighted\n\tm.statuses[\"a\"] = &providerStatus{}\n\tm.statuses[\"b\"] = &providerStatus{}\n\tm.vp.SetContent(\"baseline\")\n\n\tm.Update(statusMsg{provider: \"b\", line: \"line for b\"}) // not highlighted\n\tif m.vp.View() != \"baseline\" { // adjust assertion to however baseline content is compared\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"viewport refreshed for a non-highlighted provider\")\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n",
        "level": 2
      },
      {
        "title": "3. Rendering functions",
        "content": "\n`viewPicking`, `viewLimit`, `viewRunning`, `View` have zero coverage. Full snapshot testing is low-value given ANSI styling noise, but there are real assertions worth making: they must not panic on a zero-value model (before any `WindowSizeMsg`), and key content should appear.\n\n```go\nfunc TestView_NoPanicOnZeroValueModel(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tfor _, s := range []screen{screenPicking, screenLimit, screenRunning} {\n\t\tm.screen = s\n\t\tfunc() {\n\t\t\tdefer func() {\n\t\t\t\tif r := recover(); r != nil {\n\t\t\t\t\tt.Fatalf(\"View() panicked on screen %v: %v\", s, r)\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t}()\n\t\t\t_ = m.View()\n\t\t}()\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestViewPicking_ShowsSelectionCount(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.selected[0] = true\n\tout := m.viewPicking()\n\tif !strings.Contains(out, fmt.Sprintf(\"1 of %d selected\", len(providers))) {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"selection count not rendered:\\n%s\", out)\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n",
        "level": 2
      },
      {
        "title": "4. `runCrawler` / `runHeadless` / `startRun` â€” the real gap",
        "content": "\nThese are the parts of the app that actually do something (invoke the Python crawler), and they're currently **only testable by running a real `uv` process against `apps/crawler`** â€” slow, environment-dependent, and not something CI should rely on for unit coverage. To make this testable, `runCrawler` needs the command construction extracted or injected, e.g.:\n\n```go\n// proposed seam â€” not present today\ntype commandFactory func(name string, limit int, crawlerDir string) *exec.Cmd\n\nfunc runCrawlerWith(mkCmd commandFactory, name string, limit int, crawlerDir string, onLine func(string)) error {\n\tcmd := mkCmd(name, limit, crawlerDir)\n\t...\n}\n```\n\nOnce that seam exists, or in the meantime using `exec.Command` pointed at a test fixture script (`testdata/fake_uv.sh` that echoes fixed lines and exits with a controlled code), these become testable:\n\n- **Streaming behavior**: multiple stdout lines are each delivered to `onLine` in order, as they arrive (not batched).\n- **stderr folded into stdout**: confirm `cmd.Stderr = cmd.Stdout` actually causes stderr lines to reach `onLine` too.\n- **Non-zero exit** â†’ `runCrawler` returns a non-nil error from `cmd.Wait()`.\n- **`cmd.StdoutPipe()` failure path** (`err != nil` from `StdoutPipe`) â€” currently unreachable/untested; likely only fails if called twice on the same cmd, worth at least documenting as untestable via a comment if not worth the effort.\n- **`cmd.Start()` failure** (binary not found) â†’ error returned immediately, no goroutine leak.\n\n```go\nfunc TestRunCrawler_StreamsLinesAndPropagatesExitError(t *testing.T) {\n\t// requires a fixture script on PATH or invoked via absolute path standing\n\t// in for `uv`; skip if not present rather than failing CI on missing tooling.\n\tscript := filepath.Join(\"testdata\", \"fake_uv.sh\")\n\tif _, err := os.Stat(script); err != nil {\n\t\tt.Skip(\"fixture script not present\")\n\t}\n\n\tvar got []string\n\terr := runCrawler(\"midi-madagasikara\", 3, \"testdata\", func(line string) {\n\t\tgot = append(got, line)\n\t})\n\tif len(got) == 0 {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"no lines streamed\")\n\t}\n\t// fixture should exit non-zero to exercise the error path\n\tif err == nil {\n\t\tt.Fatal(\"expected error from non-zero exit, got nil\")\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n**`runHeadless`**: with `runCrawler` injectable, cover:\n- all providers run concurrently (use a fake that blocks on a channel to assert overlap, not serialization).\n- a single provider's error is printed but does not abort the others (`wg.Wait()` still completes for all).\n- `names` containing an unknown provider â€” currently no validation; `runCrawler` will be called with a bogus name and just fail downstream. Worth a test asserting this doesn't panic and produces an error line, plus considering whether validation should happen at the `main.go` boundary instead (see below).\n\n**`startRun`**: same DI problem â€” it hardcodes the `runCrawler` call inside the goroutine. Once injectable, cover: goroutines are only spawned for `m.selected[i] == true` entries, `m.pending` equals the number of selected providers before any goroutine completes, `m.runOrder` preserves the original `providers` list order (not selection order).\n\n---\n\n",
        "level": 2
      },
      {
        "title": "5. Missing input validation (edge cases, not just tests)",
        "content": "\nThese aren't just test gaps â€” they're behavior gaps worth deciding on and then testing:\n\n- `-providers` flag: `strings.Split(*providersFlag, \",\")` on an unknown provider name (e.g. `-providers=typo-provider`) silently passes it through to `runCrawler`, which will just fail per-provider with no upfront validation. A test (and probably a fix) for \"unknown provider name in `-providers` flag\" is missing.\n- `-providers=\"\"` (empty string) â†’ `strings.Split(\"\", \",\")` yields `[\"\"]`, a single empty-string provider name â€” untested and probably unintended.\n- Duplicate provider names in `-providers=a,a,b` â€” currently runs `a` twice concurrently, no dedup.\n- `-limit` negative via CLI flag â€” `flag.Int` will accept a negative int; only the TUI's `screenLimit` handler rejects negatives. Headless mode has no equivalent guard, so `-limit=-5` reaches `runCrawler` unchecked.\n\n---\n\n",
        "level": 2
      },
      {
        "title": "6. Integration test gap",
        "content": "\nThere is no test exercising the full `main()` binary end-to-end (build the binary, run `-headless -providers=<fixture> -crawler-dir=<fixture>`, assert on stdout). Given the actual crawler is a separate Python subprocess, a light integration test using a fake `crawler-dir` containing a stub `main.py` (or a stub `uv` shim on `PATH`) would catch regressions in flag wiring, `runHeadless` fan-out, and per-provider output prefixing (`\"[%s] %s\\n\"`) that no unit test currently covers.\n\n---\n\n",
        "level": 2
      },
      {
        "title": "Suggested priority order",
        "content": "1. Pure functions (`articlesSaved`, `truncate`, `countSelected`, `highlighted`, `layout`) â€” zero risk, immediate coverage.\n2. `handleKey`/`Update` state machine â€” highest behavioral value, no external dependencies needed.\n3. Extract a `commandFactory` seam in `runCrawler` so subprocess behavior becomes unit-testable; add the `startRun`/`runHeadless` tests once that seam exists.\n4. Add the fixture-based integration test for `main()` last, since it's the slowest and most environment-sensitive.",
        "level": 2
      }
    ],
